sub: READ THIS BEFORE YOU POST A NEW THREAD
com:
/cgl/ is a board for the following:

• Cosplay
• Lolita
• J-fashion
• Conventions & gatherings
• Sewing & prop-making
• Craftsmanship tools/materials & tutorials
• LARPing
• Discussing accessories such as wigs/circle lenses/prosthetics/makeup (These must be within the context of the board-related topics listed above; weight loss threads should be kept in /fit/, beauty and fashion generals should be kept in /fa/)

Our board rules are simple:

• Thread content must be related to one of the categories covered in the list above. Off-topic threads and replies will be deleted.
• Singling people out maliciously is not tolerated and will result in a ban. 4chan is not your personal army. The singling out rule applies to vendetta threads and replies being made to attack a specific person, as well as predatory behavior like doxing. Discussing an individual in general isn't against the rules as long as it's done within context of cosplay/lolita/j-fashion.
• Advertising and spamming are not allowed.
• This is a work-safe board.

If you encounter a post that is in violation of these rules, USE THE REPORT BUTTON! Please help us keep the board healthy and free of off-topic posts!

Helpful Links:

- Tutorial Database: http://cosplaytutorial.com/list.php
- /cgl/ general: http://pastebin.com/2E2BmDDc
- Taobao: http://pastebin.com/B2KSFQUM
- Lolibrary: http://lolibrary.org/
- Hello Lace: http://hellolace.net/
- Cosplay dot com: http://www.cosplay.com/

com:
Sewing Thread: post your sewing related questions here.

Sewing noob here. Pic related is an issue I'm running into, the material is 4 way stretch nylon. When sewing the binding to the panel it keeps getting pulled right, throwing everything off and forcing me to either lift the foot multiple times to realign, or just ruining it and making me restart. What could be the issues here - am I using the wrong type of foot? Should I use lighter foot pressure? Thanks, all help is appreciated
last_replies:
[{'no': 10823328, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)19:26:54', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823327
Have you used a knit scallop trim before? If so, do you have any recommendations for good trim?', 'time': 1670891214, 'resto': 10817921}, {'no': 10823341, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)20:37:16', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823262
ntayrt, but why didn't you just say that in your original comment instead of waiting for anon to reply and ask?', 'time': 1670895436, 'resto': 10817921}, {'no': 10823352, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)22:15:04', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823262
That post was replying to someone asking if they could sew a blouse pattern with knit fabric…it doesn’t have anything to do with cardigans.', 'time': 1670901304, 'resto': 10817921}, {'no': 10823368, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)00:40:09', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823352
no, it was a cutsew. anon probably responded to the wrong post.', 'time': 1670910009, 'resto': 10817921}, {'no': 10823374, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)04:26:07', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10822843
You’ll end up with a baggy cutsew with wobbly seams. Patterns for wovens have positive ease included whereas patterns for knits have zero or negative ease. Patterns for knits also have less curved armscyes and sleeve caps. Often the front and back armscyes in knit patterns are identical while in woven patterns they’re different. I’m not sure how to explain this (ESL) but with stretch fabrics it’s better to let the fabric do the shaping, whereas with wovens you have to make the seams curve properly around the body for the garment to fit. Patterns for knits don’t have darts for the same reason. It’s also more difficult to sew complex curves on a serger.
You can use an existing t-shirt as a pattern like the other anon suggested or look for a pattern designed for knits. ONS has several cutsew patterns with Peter Pan collars but I don’t think any of them have a front button closure, so you’d have to add that yourself. I’d recommend using special stretchy fusible interfacing for the button placket, neckline facing and maybe the cuffs.

>>10823328
Nayrt but I don’t think I’ve ever seen stretchy scallop trim of the kind you’re looking for anywhere, and I spend a lot of time looking at trims. You could use non-stretch trim and accept that whatever edge you sew it on is going to lose its stretch, or you can use the shell tuck hem. I have several (store-bought) knit tops and even a cardigan with the shell tuck hem and it looks really cute.', 'filename': 'F1EB203F-F54D-4FBA-BF96-79C5C62EE009', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 1684, 'h': 1125, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 83, 'tim': 1670923567746871, 'time': 1670923567, 'md5': 'Ji/MVcVx7A3AobevDizYeA==', 'fsize': 1451634, 'resto': 10817921}]

sub: Slow death of the Japanese second-hand market?
com:
I've noticed that the online Japanese second-hand market seems to be slowly dying over the past couple of years. This doesn't seem to be affecting just lolita fashion but also other weeb hobbies like merch collection.

Have you noticed this slow-down in your substyle or hobby? Do you agree or disagree? What do you think is happening?
last_replies:
[{'no': 10823307, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)17:22:57', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823293
The Japanese are caring less and less about condition. They haven’t been as meticulous about posting damages either in the past five or so years. The secondhand goods I’ve bought lately have undisclosed issues that would be impossible to overlook.

Some sellers in Japan are now scamming and lying about the condition just like Western lolitas do.', 'time': 1670883777, 'resto': 10823257}, {'no': 10823311, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)17:30:51', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'For me personally, the best time to buy japanese 2nd hand was from 2010-2013. There was an abundance of cheap classic on the market, which is basically non-existent today. By 2015 I noticed that it got less and by 2018 the market was more or less dead. Imo it has to do with brands closing/pushing out less frequent releases, and that most Japanese lolitas from the 2000s/early 2010s when it was very popular in Japan already graduated from the fashion. Nowadays lolita is very niche in Japan, it only makes sense that there is less of it on the market.', 'time': 1670884251, 'resto': 10823257}, {'no': 10823345, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)20:57:58', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823257

What is Lolita fashion culture for you ?

[{'no': 10823238, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)10:11:13', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823105
unfortunately lolita is fast fashion with cheap fabric and poor construction mostly made in china, we just pay for the prints at this point..

>>10823103
>lolita culture
pick your poison of larpers or gossipy hags. i guess not mutually exclusive. the larpers are either teenagers who don't even wear the fashion yet, or young adults that shoulve gotten into historical reenactment instead. the toxic shit talkers are late teens/early twenties girls that think they're in a popularity contest against eachother, and the aging spite driven women that got bullied in highschool and now live to pit younger prettier girls against each other in social cage matches.

>looks and clothing or certain mindset/is it counterculture/is it feminist
mindset is important for some fashions/cultures but I think our society has progressed to the point that the rebellious aspect is no longer a factor, basically anything goes and everyone is allowed to be whatever they say they are, if they look the part. subcultures have been commodified and sold off, and it's mainstream to be pretty accepting of everything now, you might look like an autistic retard for wearing lolita but the only people that are going to bully you for it are other lolitas.

it was really unique to be able to dress extremely feminine and still be rebellious; most nonconforming fashion is a lot edgier and more masculine, so it's kind of cool that a woman can be so frilly it's unacceptable, where femininity is usually inoffensive and docile. i think that modern femininity has pushed women to become more like men in every way, when it should be a celebration of femininity and not a movement for butch bull dykes and tranners to bastardize what it means to be a woman as badly as the west bastardized lolita.

>are there certain behaviours and values you connect
i basically learned to shop secondhand and DIY everything from lolita, and it has carried over into all other aspects of my life.', 'filename': '1609690326606', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 640, 'h': 771, 'tn_w': 103, 'tn_h': 125, 'tim': 1670857873246204, 'time': 1670857873, 'md5': '4ORrO9CiDTluYBqbp3pT9g==', 'fsize': 55888, 'resto': 10823103}, {'no': 10823260, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)12:45:17', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823150
>be a cutie sweetheart
Cringe', 'time': 1670867117, 'resto': 10823103}, {'no': 10823291, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)15:58:18', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>Is it just the looks and the clothing or is there a certain mindset?
Definitely about the clothes and how they represent different forms of the "eternal maiden". Some girls are collectors of quality brand with years of experience under their belt and make refined looks. Some girls are new and make embarrassing coord choices while overtly defending said poor choices. And of course any combination in between. Ultimately, like attracts like and the community at large is divided by those with similar tastes.

Is it counterculture?
At best it is slow fashion that embraces female ideology with bo regards to cater to males. At worst it's cancerous social media garbage that breaks the rules in egregious ways. In total, yes, as it doesn't follow more common styles.', 'time': 1670878698, 'resto': 10823103}, {'no': 10823296, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)16:06:23', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823291

>Is Lolita in the form of today still feminist?
Most importantly it's feminist second to aesthetic and self identity. A woman doesn't need to be a lolita to reject sex culture, nor does she need to dress in a masculine manner. If anything, the fucked up perceptions of males in the US and Japan about young girls would make some argue that the style is "prodding the bull" so to speak; lolitas claiming it's all projection often doesn't help the case. It's Feminist in that a woman chose the fashion for herself, but it certainly doesn't come without baggage.

>Are there certain behaviours and values you connect to your love and wear of Lolita fashion?
As other anons mentioned, it's very common to see folks with quiet and traditional hobbies like crafting, embroidering etc. To me it's more surprising to find lolitas who *don't* have some sort of creative or unusual hobby outside of brand hunting, but on that note. the ones who are only fashion obsessed tend to be dull folk to interact with.', 'time': 1670879183, 'resto': 10823103}, {'no': 10823302, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)17:01:00', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10823103
>Is lolita in the form of today still feminist?
Whenever this comes up anons seem to argue between 1) lolita is “feminist” because it’s designed to appreciate the beauty of femininity instead of appealing to men, or 2) lolita is “not feminist” because each lolita has different motivations and political opinions.
Who knows the answer, but it’s annoying how some anons get triggered by the association of “SJW” ideas with their precious loleets, ignoring that “feminism” in this context is more about the idea that women can have interests not revolving around appealing to men and reproducing, it’s not the SJW strawman feminism that says you’re a terrible person if you DO like appealing to men.
But the worst argument of all has got to be “lolita is just clothes, so it can’t have any political or cultural meaning.” That’s an instant ‘opinion discarded’, if you can’t even introspect for a second to ask yourself *why* you like certain clothes. If clothing choices didn’t have social and cultural messages embedded in them we’d all be wearing identical onesies designed to optimize convenience and comfort like in the movie wall-e.

> Are there certain behaviours and values you connect to your love and wear of Lolita fashion?
Love and appreciation for craft, for sure. We hoard and obsess over the details of our burando and feel emotional pain when brand quality goes downhill. This is also why so many lolitas have art and crafting hobbies like the other anons said, because we like to be surrounded with and produce visually beautiful things.', 'time': 1670882460, 'resto': 10823103}]

Carpet beetles are such a pain. If it helps, they typically only eat organic matter. (Save cotton, never had an issue with that and resources say they usually aren't interested in cotton.) So all you have to do is keep anything made of organic materials, such as wool or a wool blend, sealed away. They will eat blends that are part synthetic part natural fibers, like acrylic/wool sweaters, so heads up on that. Garment bags or hat boxes work well and I usually stick a sachet of a natural repellent in with it (lavender is a popular one) as well as a moisture absorbing packet. name: Anonymous
com:
I doubt there's more than two or three brazilians in here, but I still want to discuss some matters about this event.

It happens since 2014 and it seeks out to bring the experience of the San Diego Comic Con. I don't know SDCC at all, but what I can say is that the event has grown to such a level that is any disaster happens, people would die stomped, and the life of the average attendee is terrible: expensive food, lots of lines, horrible bathrooms, and basically all you can do is shop (200,000+ people in the four days of the event do that to you).

Plus the tickets are growing more and more expensive - the price of one day buys one a half or two tickets for other major events in Brazil.

And to top it off, many content creators are getting denied for having no "synergy" with the comic con and its themed. Creators that were in other editions with their press credentials, and it's been the biggest fuzz in our local community.

I want to know from my /cgl/ folks - to what measure conventions in America/Europe are becoming moneygrabbers and are new 'comic cons' or cosplay events getting created out of this 'power vacuum'?

sub: Youmacon 2022 – Detroit Renaissance Center – Nov 3rd through 6th
com:
Youmacon 2022 is a go and we can't wait to see you all here in the motor city. But first there's a couple of important things you should know. Youmacon has been going on for 18 years now and is a celebration of Anime, manga, pop-culture, comics, movies, costumes and SCIENCE. If you don't like all of these things then maybe you should just stay at home.

And that brings us to the first thing we want to report- IF YOU HAVEN'T BEEN VACCINATED WE DON'T EVEN WANT YOU TO COME. STAY AWAY. WE ARE A CONVENTION FOR PEOPLE WHO BELIEVE IN SCIENCE. If you cannot get your Covid-19 vaccinations then you may only come if you get a PCR negative test on Tuesday or later. But that should be reserved for people who have a medical reason that prevents them from getting their vaccines. We will not have PCR testing available on site.

BUT IF YOU JUST DON'T WANT TO TAKE THE VACCINES BECAUSE YOU BELIEVE THE LIES AND CONSPIRACY THEORIES- THEN WE REALLY HOPE YOU JUST STAY AWAY.

All staff may check your Vaccine Passports at all times. Failure to show your Vaccine Passport at any time to any staff MAY RESULT HAVING YOUR BADGE TAKEN AND YOU BEING REMOVED FROM THE CONVENTION. name: Anonymous
com:
Hi everyone

I want to post some distressing news concerning Ohayocon 2023 and its potential future. The Conhead has made the decision concern health regulations. We were hoping for a hard vaccine+boost along with a N95 mask mandate, but simple masking will only be required if mandated by the City of Columbus. This has led to 75% of all volunteers resigning and the resignation of two vice-chairs that help organize the con. In addition, the medical volunteers have all resigned meaning Ohayocon will not have any medical staff on hand for the con for 2023. I was one of those who resigned last week and wanted the share the information. As an immunocompromised person, I almost died from contracting COVID and still suffer from the effects to this day. We’ve been ignored even more now as people don’t care about the pandemic.

Obviously Ohayocon doesn’t care about the pandemic either. I hope the Conhead reconsiders and we have a compromise.

sub: Where's a good place to start?
com:
I want to get into cosplay and congoing but I have no idea where to begin. I'm sort of intimidated by the whole thing. When I was in college my university hosted a fairly large anime convention every year, but I had no friends and I was always too embarrassed to go by myself. I wish I had gone, because now that I'm out of school I feel like it's even weirder to go to a con by myself as an adult. At least back then I would have had the excuse of begin a student.

Would it be a bad idea to go to my first con in plain clothes just to see what it's like? There aren't any con in my area that I know of, and I'm a few hours away from an major US city. Whichever cons I manage to find around me will probably be pretty tiny, which seems like a good entry point in my mind. The reason I ask is that I get the sense that there are a lot of hidden rules and shit to how this stuff works that I probably want to wrap my head around before I dive in. Or am I being overly cautious?

Then do that, show up to a con dressed and don't worry about a thing. >Do you have a character whos outfit you like and want to wear?
There are several characters I'd like to go as, but they range from super complex armor to extremely simple clothes I could probably buy off the shelf and alter. This is where that "hidden rules and shit" I mentioned comes in, I don't know what it's like to walk around in a costume all day, and I don't want to end up miserable at my first con because I decided to go as a character with full body armor with poor mobility.
>Do you have the means to buy or craft it?
My education and career focus on manufacturing and model making. Although I've never actually cosplayed or built my own costume before, I have tons of experience with airbrushing, vacuum forming, 3D printing, foam work, etc. I feel pretty confident I could make something that looks decent.', 'time': 1669579228, 'resto': 10820863}, {'no': 10820868, 'now': '11/27/22(Sun)16:15:41', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '> I get the sense that there are a lot of hidden rules and shit to how this stuff works that I probably want to wrap my head around before I dive in.

competition is very competitive, most cons will divide the different "tiers" into amounts of awards won, so you see some really good seamstresses/tailors even in the entry level division. some of them smurf as well, where they don't compete and just try to get really good at crafting (and then enter the entry level and clear house). a lot of competitions have meh judges and I've seen some really dogshit costumes win because they felt bad for the cosplayer, etc etc. it's very subjective and a lot of the judges are kind of dogshit.

the vast majority (95%) of cosplay though, is people buying the same 3-4 versions of whatever character they want. it's so limited that you can basically look at someone and go "ok they got the ezcosplay version of Daki's outfit" (for example). it's especially visible if the factories got the color or design slightly wrong; I remember when SpyXFamily started, one company made Loid's suit this weird way-too-blue teal color instead of the olive he's meant to have. made it really easy to see who bought it off that site.

online clout is a massive crapshoot and people put in a FUCKTON of effort to be popular (editing photos, timing when to release them, posting on different avenues (tiktok, reels, etc), posting on reddit, twitter, etc etc). it's much easier if you're a cute girl ofc (since coomers don't care about quality, if you buy your outfits, etc etc), but I've seen some other really good cosplayers make it big.', 'time': 1669566806, 'resto': 10820770}, {'no': 10820833, 'now': '11/27/22(Sun)12:20:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10820784
>>10820770
Like any other hobby, it can be as casual or competitive as you want it to be. There are plenty of people who create insane builds and don't participate in competitions at all. On the flip side, there are a number of well known "professional" cosplayers who only create mediocre stuff at best.
I personally don't have an interest in participating in cosplay competitions because I tend to cosplay obscure and unpopular characters.
And if you're talking about informally competing with others, trying to outdo your friends for example, that really depends on your friend group and if they are the competitive type. I find that having a friend to informally compete with is good motivation to push my craftsmanship.
It would be like asking "How competitive is fishing?" There are people who participate in formal tournaments and even make a living off of it, and there's others who just want to do something fun with their friends. No one is going to come up to you at a con and tell you your costume sucks or bully you for it, even if it's some shitty Amazon thing you couldn't even be bothered to steam the wrinkles out of. They might say something behind your back to their friends, but that's just life and you can't do anything about that.', 'time': 1669569631, 'resto': 10820770}, {'no': 10820869, 'now': '11/27/22(Sun)16:29:46', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10820833
Parroting this. I’ve seen online cosplayers make the most intricate props I’ve seen that they deserve to be displayed on a mahogany side table. Because of online streaming, modern anime (hallmark of cringey nerds) is so marketable that the industry itself runs on tropes you can tick off like a checklist. Mainstream recognizes a marketable niche, enter the “loss in quality control”. There’s several Genshin cosplayers out there who have never even touched the game. In the end, cosplayers are all just cringey nerds dressing up as their favorite vidya game characters. Some care about accuracy and are really good at it, and some couldn’t give less of a fuck about what fabric their gloves are made of as long as they can get into the spirit of con-going.
